The trooper was bullshitting you. The law is here...

http://tinyurl.com/2bobbv

Basically it says...

For purposes of this section, &quot;motorcycle helmet&quot; means a
protective covering for the head consisting of a hard outer shell,
padding adjacent to and inside the outer shell, and a neck or chin
strap type retention system, with a sticker indicating that the
motorcycle helmet meets standards established by the United States
Department of Transportation

Since the law went into effect a few years ago I know of no one
that's been hassled when they have a DOT sticker on their helmet,
even if the only thing on the sticker were the letters DOT, which of
course is fake.

It also says that the State Patrol can only amend the rule only when
it pertains to glasses, goggles and face shields, BUT not helmets.

It doesn't say anywhere (that I can find) that they can take your
vehicle, except in a new law pertaining to drivers licenses...

Regarding the &quot;new law&quot; he was talking about, it authorizes an
officer to impound your vehicle if you're not properly licensed
to operate the vehicle. That includes an endorsement.

But, as one cop told me a few years ago... &quot;It's not my job to
know the exact wording of every law. That's what a judge is
for.&quot;

