I understand completely.

FWIW, he was on the road to the left of the intersection on the other side
of a partially opened construction gate behind a bunch of orange and white
barrels with a Road Closed sign (must have been bored out of his mind).

That's not to say he wasn't harboring some ill-will for other reasons, but
taking that out on me is utter bullshit. His profession is dealing with
these situtations, he needed to calm down before getting out of the cruiser.
When I have a bad morning at work, I don't take it out on my peers, or get
home and take it out on my wife and kids.

That said, I was cutting him all the slack he needed by keeping my mouth
shut and just taking it. I was in no hurry to get away, and I would have sat
there until he calmed down. He was the one in control of the time table. Not
to mention that he is as responsible for his actions, as I am, and he owed
it to me to not be a dick, since I was trying to have a calm discussion.
Clearly I was not a wild eyed, drugged out, or alcohol impaired lunatic.

At this point, I'm just happy to still have my license. Although I do harbor
the resentment of the additional cost of hiring a lawyer to defend myself
should _that_ cop show up at the hearing, which he did not. A state police
representative was there instead.

I still count the lawyer fee as  well worth retaining my license, but that
additional expense could have been prevented, if the dolt had had a two way
conversation with me, rather than just yelling, and threatening to see me in
court to petition that my license be permanently revoked (which he repeated
three times during his diatribe, before going on his way with a final, &quot;see
you in court&quot;).

I feel bad for his kids if they ever fuck up in front of him. Holy shit.

Basically, I cost myself a couple hundred in fines and a few hundred more in
insurance premiums over the next three years. That was _my_ doing, and I
take/took full responsibility for my actions. But it cost me an extra grand
for defense of my driving priviliges, because _his_ emotions got the better
of him.  I sure do wish I could get _that_ money back.

So, yeah, I'm a little bitter toward state cops who come across as civilian
haters.

And now, I've got yet another ticket which I _have_ to contest, rather than
just accept and pay the fine, or find myself taking driver re-training. I
put my passenger side wheels over the rumble strip and into the breakdown
lane to make my exit from the highway. State cop pulls me over for a BDL
violation, and actually gives me a ticket that we both know is going to get
dismissed by the magistrate. He was just being a dick.

Honestly, I saw him sitting there and didn't think anything of what I had
done. Probably because unlike so many others at that intersection, I
actually refuse to go all four wheels into the brakedown lane to get to the
exit lane when the light is red. That is, I'm mindful of the law, and figure
it's bad form to violate it so blantantly, but two wheels? Oh, come on, I
wasn't even _half_ a car width over the line, and for only about 20 feet of
forward travel.

As I past by him in the exit lane 50 feet further down, he pulled out of the
stopped traffic, got behind me and put on his lights. I was completely
dumbfounded that he was actually pulling me over. When I asked him what I
had done,  he sarcastically remarked, &quot;Do you _always_ drive in the
breakdown lane?&quot; At that point, I had had enough of state cops, and didn't
say a word.

What really ticks me off though, is that I _really do_ commute every day at
60-65 in a 55 (bike or car), where (almost) everyone else is doing 65-70.
I'm one of the good guys out there. I challenge any state trooper to follow
me around without me knowing it for a month, without hassle for the
occasional minor fuck up, or the occasional hammering of the throttle for a
brief distance, and do an actual critique of my driving.

I just let the pack go by, and keep my distance from everyone. I've been
driving since I was 10, and on the road since 14. On the same roads. I've
seen it all, done it all, lived to tell about it, and grown old enough to
prefer to just take my time 95% of the time, and to always put safety first,
especially when I decide to pull out the stops every now and again, hammer
the throttle, and increase the risk of _personal_ injury.

Bottom line is there seems to be too much enforcement of the wrong traffic
laws for my liking around here, and not enough of the ones that matter day
to day. Like cagers going 70 MPH in a 55 with less than a one second gap
between them. I've checked the books. That constitutes driving to endanger
at the discretion of the LEOs. Problem is, they do it too, and in so doing,
promote it among others.

Frankly I blame the safety features in contemporary cars, for a lot of the
actual danger out there on the road. In the old days, if you were smart, you
knew that crashing at 70 was going to end badly. These days, folks seem to
think they're gonna survive no matter what happens, because they're
commuting in a fortess of safety. Doing 80MPH with a one second gap between
bumpers is nothing to them.

Good luck, I say.

